                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="1" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Still need someone to explain to me why its equitable for us to get 25% critical DoT's PLUS 13,15,19% whatever it is Critical DD.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></font id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"><br /><br />Think of it this way Waldina, a 10% increase in nuke damage for a Wizard is a 10% increase in damage.  <br /><br />But for a Necromancer to get a 10% increase in damage, he or she must get a pet that is 10% better than the previous, a nuke 10% better than previous, and a DoT 10% better than previous.  In the past, we got the nuke increase, but that was it.  Now, most of us would like to see the balance offered as a DoT increase.<br /><br />Example: a Wizard nukes for 1000.  <br /><br />His partner the Necromancer DoTs for 400 (over time), sends pet for 300 (over time), and nukes for 300.  <br /><br />A 10% nuke increase makes the Wizard do 1100.  <br /><br />A 10% nuke increase lets the Necromancer do 330.  <br /><br />Upgraded wizard damage is 1100<br /><br />Upgraded necromancer damage (including pet & DoT) is 1030.  <br /><br />See now why many of us think it is fair for us to improve our DoT damage, while retaining the nuke chances?  <br /><br />For classes with both nukes and DoTs (us, Shamen, Druids and Mages) to remain comparable, we must increase in each area, not just one.  <br /><br />(If we had to choose just one, though, I'd choose DoTs, as I cast them more often than nukes whenever possible.)</span id="msg"></font></td>
